message.content: One of the most significant events that happened in Ireland in the past 100 years is the Good Friday Agreement, signed on April 10, 1998. This agreement marked a major milestone in the Northern Ireland peace process, bringing an end to decades of conflict known as "The Troubles." The Good Friday Agreement established a power-sharing government in Northern Ireland, recognized the principle of consent for any change in the region's constitutional status, and created institutions for cross-border cooperation between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland. It has played a crucial role in maintaining peace and stability in the region since its signing.
